<DOC><DOCNO> AP890113-0228 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1430EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-Heartland-SteelFacts Adv25   01-13 0291</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Heartland-Steel Facts, Adv 25,0297</SECOND><HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, Jan. 25, and Thereafter</HEAD><HEAD>Figures for Recovering Steel Industry</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Heartland-Steel Town Revival</HEAD><HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here are some facts about the steel industry, provided by theAmerican Iron and Steel Institute. They represent reports from 25companies representing 80 percent of the industry.   _ Profits-Losses: The nation's steel industry is expected to posta 1988 profit of about $2 billion. In 1987, profits were $1.02billion, following losses of almost $12 billion in 1982-86.   The rising profits are attributed to a general strengthening inthe world steel market and a moderate increase in demand.   _ Shipments: Domestic steel mill shipments are estimated to haverisen from 76.7 million tons in 1987 to about 83 million tons in1988 _ an 8.2 percent increase.   _ Production: Raw steel production jumped from 89.2 million tonsin 1987 to almost 100 million tons in 1988 _ a 12 percent increase.   _ Employment: Average industry employment in 1988 was 170,000,slightly above the 1987 average of 163,000, the lowest since theinstitute started keeping records in 1933. The industry posted arecord-high employment of 650,200 in 1953.   _ Imports: Imports in 1988 will have accounted for about 20.5percent of the steel shipped to consumers, compared with 20.9percent in 1987. Imports reached a high of 26.4 percent in 1984, theyear when the Voluntary Restraint Agreements set a goal of reducingimports to 20.2 percent of the U.S. market. The agreement expiresthis year.   _ State Production: Indiana leads the nation in steel production,with about 22 percent of the steel made there. Ohio accounts for 18percent and Pennsylvania 13 percent.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Jan. 25</NOTE></DOC>